Leave room.

00:39:28.710 --> 00:39:38.620
All right, so let's get precise.

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:50.620
What I want to do is
show that we can always

00:39:50.620 --> 00:39:53.160
find a local Lorentz frame.

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.660
And what I mean
by that is that I

00:40:09.660 --> 00:40:12.990
want to be able to
show that I can always

00:40:12.990 --> 00:40:17.370
do a change of my coordinates,
a change of my representation

00:40:17.370 --> 00:40:23.220
such that, at some point, I can
convert the metric of spacetime

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:26.220
into the metric we used
in special relativity,

00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:28.530
at least over some
finite region.

00:40:58.100 --> 00:41:00.382
So let me define a
couple of quantities

00:41:00.382 --> 00:41:02.590
and then let me formulate
the way this calculation is

00:41:02.590 --> 00:41:03.190
going to work.

00:41:06.290 --> 00:41:14.560
Let us let coordinates
with unbarred Greek indices

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.470
be the coordinate
system that we start in.

00:41:24.460 --> 00:41:29.260
And let's say that, in
this representation,

00:41:29.260 --> 00:41:32.720
the metric is G alpha beta.

00:41:35.710 --> 00:41:38.840
Let's demand that
there exists a set of

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:40.880
coordinates that
I will represent

00:41:40.880 --> 00:41:41.960
with bars on the indices.

00:41:45.340 --> 00:41:46.990
When we transform to
these coordinates,

00:41:46.990 --> 00:42:10.060
I want spacetime to be Lorentz
at least in the vicinity

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:11.590
of some point or some event.

00:42:19.318 --> 00:42:20.886
We'll call that event p.

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:50.200
So we will assume that
there is some mapping

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:53.140
between these
coordinates, so there's

00:42:53.140 --> 00:42:55.040
no nasty singularities there.

00:42:58.830 --> 00:43:01.650
And it's nothing that
we can't deal with.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.300
So we can do it in
either direction,

00:43:09.300 --> 00:43:14.820
but let's say x alpha
is x alpha of p written

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:16.590
as some function of these guys.

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.215
And so there's a transformation
matrix between the two of them.

00:43:26.930 --> 00:43:31.890
It takes the usual form, OK?

00:43:31.890 --> 00:43:42.050
So mathematically, the way
I'm going to show this is I

00:43:42.050 --> 00:43:56.400
want to show that we can
find a coordinate system such

00:43:56.400 --> 00:44:02.390
that, if I compute
the spacetime metric

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:07.190
and the barred
representation, this is always

00:44:07.190 --> 00:44:12.065
going to be given by doing
this coordinate transformation.

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:20.060
Then I get the metric
of flat spacetime

00:44:20.060 --> 00:44:22.445
over as large a
region as possible.

00:44:33.664 --> 00:44:37.685
OK, we know we're not going to
be able to do it everywhere.

00:44:37.685 --> 00:44:39.060
What I want to
show is that I can

00:44:39.060 --> 00:44:42.540
make that happen at the point
p and that the functional

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:44.780
behavior of this thing
is sufficiently flat

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:49.237
that it remains at
this over some region.

00:44:49.237 --> 00:44:51.570
So let me just sketch what
the logic of this calculation

00:44:51.570 --> 00:44:52.195
is going to be.

00:45:16.630 --> 00:45:21.320
So what we're going
to do is expand.

00:45:21.320 --> 00:45:27.430
So remember g is a function.

00:45:27.430 --> 00:45:29.650
All of these l's are functions.

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:31.150
So what I'm going
to do is I'm going

00:45:31.150 --> 00:45:33.820
to think of this
whole thing as itself

00:45:33.820 --> 00:45:35.430
being some kind of a function.

00:45:35.430 --> 00:45:37.150
I'm going to expand
in the Taylor series.

00:45:56.673 --> 00:45:58.340
There's something
really cool that we're

00:45:58.340 --> 00:45:59.080
going to have to do with this.

00:45:59.080 --> 00:46:00.280
I mean, if I do this
in general, you're

00:46:00.280 --> 00:46:02.160
going to get something
pretty vomitous It's

00:46:02.160 --> 00:46:03.200
a giant, giant mess.

00:46:03.200 --> 00:46:03.700
OK?

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:06.360
You might worry, what the hell
are we going to do with this?

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:08.568
OK, but there's something
really cool that we can do.

00:46:08.568 --> 00:46:11.650
So we are given the metric g.

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:14.440
But we are free to pick our
coordinate transformation to be

00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:17.000
whatever we want it to be.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:23.620
So what we are going
to do is compare

00:46:23.620 --> 00:46:31.030
the degrees of
freedom offered by

00:46:31.030 --> 00:46:32.950
the coordinate transformation.

00:46:32.950 --> 00:46:34.840
Which again, I emphasize,
we are free to make

00:46:34.840 --> 00:46:36.132
that whatever we need it to be.

00:46:44.382 --> 00:46:46.840
So the coordinate transformation
and its derivative, right?

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:48.940
We're free to play
around with this thing.

00:46:48.940 --> 00:46:49.915
It's under our control.

00:47:00.230 --> 00:47:03.530
To the constraints
that are imposed

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:05.378
by the metric and its
derivatives, which

00:47:05.378 --> 00:47:05.920
we are given.

00:47:23.470 --> 00:47:27.150
So what we're
essentially going to do--

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:29.730
so in a moment or two,
I'm going to write out

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:34.140
very schematically what this
coordinate transformation is

00:47:34.140 --> 00:47:37.170
going to look like when I
do the Taylor expansion.

00:47:37.170 --> 00:47:39.420
And what I want to
do is, essentially,

00:47:39.420 --> 00:47:42.690
just count up how many
degrees of freedom

00:47:42.690 --> 00:47:45.030
the coordinate system
offers me, count up

00:47:45.030 --> 00:47:46.860
the number of
constraints that need

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:49.620
to be matched in order to
effect this transformation,

00:47:49.620 --> 00:47:52.220
see whether I've got enough.

00:47:52.220 --> 00:47:54.162
Assess what we
learn from that, OK?

00:48:02.610 --> 00:48:05.070
We just set up with
a few more things

00:48:05.070 --> 00:48:06.270
to help define the logic.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:17.670
So I'm going to write G
alpha beta as G alpha beta

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:22.360
at the point p plus x gamma.

00:48:22.360 --> 00:48:23.110
And you know what?

00:48:23.110 --> 00:48:26.950
Let's do the expansion
in the bar coordinate.

00:48:26.950 --> 00:48:34.200
Minus x gamma bar at point
p times the derivative

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:34.850
at point p.

00:48:39.502 --> 00:48:40.960
And then I'm going
to get something

00:48:40.960 --> 00:48:49.180
that involves a
complicated form of x

00:48:49.180 --> 00:48:59.150
squared and second derivatives.

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:00.160
OK, this can keep going.

00:49:00.160 --> 00:49:02.500
But this is going to be
enough for our purposes.

00:49:02.500 --> 00:49:09.650
I am likewise going to expand
my coordinate transformation

00:49:09.650 --> 00:49:10.150
matrix.

00:49:28.940 --> 00:49:31.204
Make sure I got all
my bars in place.

00:49:31.204 --> 00:49:31.704
OK.

00:49:47.615 --> 00:49:48.115
OK.

00:49:54.262 --> 00:49:55.720
So let me go over
to another board,

00:49:55.720 --> 00:49:57.740
just write down a few
more important things.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:49:58.990
And then we'll start counting.

00:50:09.510 --> 00:50:13.150
So first key thing,
which I want to note

00:50:13.150 --> 00:50:17.400
before I dig into
the calculation,

00:50:17.400 --> 00:50:25.640
is the metric at this
point, its derivative,

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:29.590
its second derivative.

00:50:29.590 --> 00:50:31.790
These have been handed to us.

00:50:31.790 --> 00:50:32.290
OK?

00:50:32.290 --> 00:50:34.240
So we have no freedom
to play with these.

00:50:34.240 --> 00:50:35.835
These are going to
give us constraints

00:50:35.835 --> 00:50:36.835
that we need to satisfy.

00:50:51.320 --> 00:51:01.610
The coordinate transformation
in its various derivatives,

00:51:01.610 --> 00:51:03.310
we are free to specify these.

00:51:08.166 --> 00:51:11.700
These are our
degrees of freedom.

00:51:20.670 --> 00:51:23.630
OK, so let me just
restate the calculation

00:51:23.630 --> 00:51:24.630
that we are going to do.

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:27.960
Basically, we wanted to do this.

00:51:27.960 --> 00:51:30.173
Schematically, here's
what this calculation

00:51:30.173 --> 00:51:31.090
is going to look like.

00:51:33.610 --> 00:51:35.115
And if you look
at this right now,

00:51:35.115 --> 00:51:36.990
you might think this is
going to be horrible.

00:51:36.990 --> 00:51:40.020
But we don't need to specify
every step of this thing

00:51:40.020 --> 00:51:41.250
in absolutely gory detail.

00:51:46.040 --> 00:51:57.490
What we want to do
is make this, which

00:51:57.490 --> 00:52:15.810
I can write as this guy at
point p, this guy at point p,

00:52:15.810 --> 00:52:27.150
this guy at point p plus a
term that is going to be linear

00:52:27.150 --> 00:52:30.600
in the distance from the
spacetime displacement away

00:52:30.600 --> 00:52:31.380
from point p.

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:39.420
If you want to go and multiply
this out, knock yourself out.

00:52:39.420 --> 00:52:41.880
But it suffices to
know that you are

00:52:41.880 --> 00:52:43.350
going to get some
new things that

00:52:43.350 --> 00:52:46.180
involve first derivatives
of all these quantities.

00:52:46.180 --> 00:52:56.080
So this will involve
these two things.

00:53:10.310 --> 00:53:14.677
And this will involve
second derivatives

00:53:14.677 --> 00:53:15.510
of all these things.

00:53:20.272 --> 00:53:21.730
Now what we're
going to do is we're

00:53:21.730 --> 00:53:24.490
going to try to make what
we would get multiplying all

00:53:24.490 --> 00:53:28.295
this out look as much
like minus 1, 1, 1,

00:53:28.295 --> 00:53:30.560
1 of the diagonal as possible.

00:53:30.560 --> 00:53:34.143
And like I said, it really just
involves accounting argument.

00:53:34.143 --> 00:53:36.310
It's actually one of my
favorite little calculations

00:53:36.310 --> 00:53:39.793
we do in this class because
it's my favorite word for this

00:53:39.793 --> 00:53:40.960
is it really looks vomitous.

00:53:40.960 --> 00:53:43.040
But it's quite elegant.

00:53:45.700 --> 00:53:49.895
And I have an
eight-year-old kid.

00:53:49.895 --> 00:53:51.520
And I'm constantly
trying to teach her,

00:53:51.520 --> 00:53:52.860
math is just all about counting.

00:53:52.860 --> 00:53:54.110
And this is a perfect example.

00:53:54.110 --> 00:53:56.770
This is really just
about counting.

00:53:56.770 --> 00:53:58.680
So let's look at this
thing at 0th order.

00:54:02.930 --> 00:54:07.760
So what I'm trying to do is
guarantee that I've got some l,

00:54:07.760 --> 00:54:09.380
which I can choose,
which will make

00:54:09.380 --> 00:54:15.260
the components of the g at
that point be minus 1, 1, 1, 1.

00:54:15.260 --> 00:54:22.550
So my constraints, the
conditions I must satisfy

00:54:22.550 --> 00:54:28.760
involve things that hit
these 4 by 4 symmetric tensor

00:54:28.760 --> 00:54:30.240
components.

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:32.150
So this guy is something
that is symmetric.

00:54:36.280 --> 00:54:38.830
Nature has just handed
me a symmetric tensor

00:54:38.830 --> 00:54:41.230
with a symmetric 4 by 4 object.

00:54:41.230 --> 00:54:44.440
Those are 10 constraints that
my transformation must satisfy.

00:54:55.590 --> 00:55:03.270
What I'm going to use to do this
is this matrix at the point p.

00:55:03.270 --> 00:55:09.870
And I'll remind you,
this matrix is just

00:55:09.870 --> 00:55:14.280
following set of partial
derivatives at that point p.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:16.290
This is also 4 by 4.

00:55:16.290 --> 00:55:20.460
It is not symmetric.

00:55:20.460 --> 00:55:29.670
So this actually gives
me 16 degrees of freedom

00:55:29.670 --> 00:55:31.691
to satisfy these constraints.

00:55:39.868 --> 00:55:40.840
Ta da!

00:55:40.840 --> 00:55:44.980
We can easily make this thing
look Lorentzian at the point p.

00:55:44.980 --> 00:55:47.290
In fact, we can do so
and have six degrees

00:55:47.290 --> 00:55:49.180
of freedom left over.

00:55:49.180 --> 00:55:52.840
Any idea what those six
degrees of freedom are?

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:55.406
Remember you're going
into a Lorentz frame.

00:55:55.406 --> 00:55:57.180
Yeah?

00:55:57.180 --> 00:55:58.830
Three rotations, three boosts.

00:55:58.830 --> 00:55:59.460
Exactly right.

00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:14.820
Boom.

00:56:14.820 --> 00:56:18.940
So not only does it
work mathematically,

00:56:18.940 --> 00:56:21.030
but there's a little
bit of leftover stuff

00:56:21.030 --> 00:56:22.890
which hopefully
hits our intuition

00:56:22.890 --> 00:56:25.512
as to how things should
behave in special relativity.

00:56:28.956 --> 00:56:31.400
OK, that's not really
good enough though, right?

00:56:31.400 --> 00:56:34.140
So I just showed that I
can do it at this point.

00:56:34.140 --> 00:56:38.132
And if I move a centimeter
away from that point, suppose,

00:56:38.132 --> 00:56:39.590
there's some really
steep gradient,

00:56:39.590 --> 00:56:41.040
and then it goes
completely to hell.

00:56:41.040 --> 00:56:41.540
OK?

00:56:41.540 --> 00:56:42.538
Then we're in trouble.

00:56:42.538 --> 00:56:43.580
So we have to keep going.

00:56:43.580 --> 00:56:45.740
We have to look at
the additional terms

00:56:45.740 --> 00:56:46.984
in this expansion.

00:56:52.420 --> 00:56:55.630
So when we do things at
0th order, we have now--

00:56:55.630 --> 00:56:57.400
so g has been handed to us.

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:01.900
We have now specified
behavior of l at that point.

00:57:01.900 --> 00:57:05.710
So l has been
completely soaked up.

00:57:05.710 --> 00:57:09.340
I don't have any more freedom
to mess around with it.

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:17.990
When I go to the next
order, OK, so the quantity

00:57:17.990 --> 00:57:23.330
that is setting my constraints
is the first derivative

00:57:23.330 --> 00:57:25.350
of this.

00:57:25.350 --> 00:57:30.806
So these are four derivatives
of my 10 metric functions.

00:57:38.100 --> 00:57:44.920
4 by 4 symmetric
by 4 components.

00:57:47.770 --> 00:57:51.165
So I have got 40
constraints I must satisfy.

00:57:59.010 --> 00:58:01.290
OK, well, the tool
that I have available,

00:58:01.290 --> 00:58:04.800
I am free to specify the
derivatives at this point.

00:58:07.560 --> 00:58:10.233
Again, remember this is
itself a partial derivative.

00:58:20.860 --> 00:58:33.540
So I've got 4 components alpha,
4 derivatives with gamma bar, 4

00:58:33.540 --> 00:58:35.640
derivatives with mu bar.

00:58:35.640 --> 00:58:39.450
Partial derivatives, it should
not matter what the order is.

00:58:39.450 --> 00:58:42.510
So this needs to be
symmetric on mu and gamma.

00:58:52.430 --> 00:58:55.720
So I, in fact, have 40 degrees
of freedom at 1st order.

00:59:03.400 --> 00:59:04.820
Perfect match.

00:59:04.820 --> 00:59:05.320
OK?

00:59:05.320 --> 00:59:06.970
So I can make my
coordinate system.

00:59:06.970 --> 00:59:11.140
Not only can I make it equal
to the Lorentz form at--

00:59:11.140 --> 00:59:14.110
I can make the spacetime
metric Lorentz at the point p,

00:59:14.110 --> 00:59:16.180
I can also make it
flat at that point p.

00:59:19.820 --> 00:59:21.950
All right, now
we're feeling cocky.

00:59:21.950 --> 00:59:24.860
So let's move on.

00:59:24.860 --> 00:59:26.130
How far can I go?

00:59:29.950 --> 00:59:31.060
I lost the page I need.

00:59:50.657 --> 00:59:52.740
OK, so now you have a
flavor for what we're doing.

00:59:52.740 --> 00:59:53.240
OK?

00:59:53.240 --> 00:59:55.250
I want to count up the
number of degrees of--

00:59:55.250 --> 00:59:57.080
sorry-- the number
of constraints

00:59:57.080 --> 00:59:59.550
that are in the metric
object, the new metric

00:59:59.550 --> 01:00:02.073
object I work with at
this order and compare it

01:00:02.073 --> 01:00:04.490
to the degrees of freedom in
the coordinate transformation

01:00:04.490 --> 01:00:05.073
at this order.

01:00:09.383 --> 01:00:11.300
So when I go to 2nd
order, my new metric thing

01:00:11.300 --> 01:00:13.430
that I'm going to be
messing around with

01:00:13.430 --> 01:00:16.050
is the second derivative.

01:00:16.050 --> 01:00:22.840
So I take two derivatives of
g alpha beta at the point p.

01:00:22.840 --> 01:00:25.770
So this again needs to be
symmetric in the derivative.

01:00:25.770 --> 01:00:38.820
So I have a symmetric 4
by 4 on these two guys.

01:00:38.820 --> 01:00:49.030
And the metric is itself 4
by 4, one alpha and beta.

01:00:49.030 --> 01:00:51.125
So there is 100
conditions, 100 constraints

01:00:51.125 --> 01:00:52.000
that we must satisfy.

01:00:55.750 --> 01:01:07.190
So let's look at the
second derivative of this.

01:01:07.190 --> 01:01:09.190
OK, so I'm going to move
this down a little bit.

01:01:21.440 --> 01:01:24.550
This is now going to look
like the third derivative

01:01:24.550 --> 01:01:25.800
when I do this transformation.

01:01:25.800 --> 01:01:27.467
So it's going to be
the third derivative

01:01:27.467 --> 01:01:43.420
of x alpha with respect to mu
bar, delta bar, and gamma bar.

01:01:43.420 --> 01:01:48.850
So I've got 4 degrees
of freedom for my alpha.

01:01:52.690 --> 01:01:56.680
And this must be
perfectly symmetric

01:01:56.680 --> 01:02:00.190
under the any interchange
of the indices mu bar,

01:02:00.190 --> 01:02:02.022
delta bar, and gamma bar.

01:02:02.022 --> 01:02:03.710
OK?

01:02:03.710 --> 01:02:07.400
This is a little exercise
in combinatorics.

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:12.170
So the number of equivalent
ways of arranging this

01:02:12.170 --> 01:02:17.570
turns out to be n
times m plus 1 times n

01:02:17.570 --> 01:02:22.860
plus 2 over 3 factorial.

01:02:22.860 --> 01:02:24.770
And I'm in 4 dimensions
for n equals 4.

01:02:27.620 --> 01:02:30.020
Work that out, and
you will find that you

01:02:30.020 --> 01:02:34.870
have 80 degrees of freedom.

01:02:42.210 --> 01:02:45.050
So what we can do
is we can always

01:02:45.050 --> 01:02:47.780
find a coordinate transformation
that makes it flat.

01:02:47.780 --> 01:02:50.570
It makes it
Lorentzian at point p.

01:02:50.570 --> 01:02:52.290
It is flat in that region.

01:02:52.290 --> 01:02:56.470
In other words, there is
no first derivative there.

01:02:56.470 --> 01:02:57.020
Sorry.

01:02:57.020 --> 01:03:00.020
Flat's not really
the right word.

01:03:00.020 --> 01:03:03.170
There is no slope
right at that point.

01:03:03.170 --> 01:03:06.430
But we cannot transfer
away the second derivative.

01:03:06.430 --> 01:03:13.100
And so what this tells me is the
coordinate freedom that we have

01:03:13.100 --> 01:03:17.260
means that we can always put our
metric into the following form.

01:03:56.198 --> 01:03:57.990
I'm just going to write
this schematically.

01:03:57.990 --> 01:04:02.580
Second derivative to
the metric and sort

01:04:02.580 --> 01:04:06.701
of the quadratic separation
in spacetime coordinate.

01:04:29.810 --> 01:04:35.110
So a couple things about
this are pretty interesting.

01:04:35.110 --> 01:04:36.870
So this is basically
telling me that we

01:04:36.870 --> 01:04:40.590
can make it Lorentz only up to
terms that look, essentially,

01:04:40.590 --> 01:04:42.570
like the second
derivative of the metric.

01:04:42.570 --> 01:04:44.640
Well, the second
derivative of any function

01:04:44.640 --> 01:04:46.690
tells you about the
curvature of that function.

01:04:46.690 --> 01:04:49.232
So this word curvature is going
to be coming up over and over

01:04:49.232 --> 01:04:50.560
and over again.

01:04:50.560 --> 01:04:53.010
We are, in fact, because
this is general relativity,

01:04:53.010 --> 01:04:53.940
we can't do everything simply.

01:04:53.940 --> 01:04:56.340
We're going to actually find
that there is a rigorous way

01:04:56.340 --> 01:04:59.550
to define a notion of curvature
that we're going to play with,

01:04:59.550 --> 01:05:02.370
which indeed looks
like two derivatives

01:05:02.370 --> 01:05:04.350
of the spacetime metric.

01:05:04.350 --> 01:05:07.440
And we are going to find it
has, I mean, it's actually

01:05:07.440 --> 01:05:10.690
going to end up looking
like a 4 index tensor.

01:05:10.690 --> 01:05:11.190
OK?

01:05:11.190 --> 01:05:14.850
So it's going to be an object
that's got 4 indices on it.

01:05:14.850 --> 01:05:19.540
Each of those indices goes over
the 4 spacetime coordinates.

01:05:19.540 --> 01:05:23.100
And so naively, it looks like
it's got 4 to the 4th power

01:05:23.100 --> 01:05:24.840
independent components.

01:05:24.840 --> 01:05:26.862
256.

01:05:26.862 --> 01:05:29.070
It has certain symmetries
we're going to see, though.

01:05:29.070 --> 01:05:31.028
And when you take into
account those symmetries

01:05:31.028 --> 01:05:32.730
and you count up
how many of those

01:05:32.730 --> 01:05:35.130
components are
actually independent,

01:05:35.130 --> 01:05:37.870
any guesses what the number
is going to turn out to be?

01:05:37.870 --> 01:05:39.310
20.

01:05:39.310 --> 01:05:42.825
Yes, it exactly compensates
for the number that cannot be

01:05:42.825 --> 01:05:44.700
zeroed out by this
coordinate transformation.

01:05:44.700 --> 01:05:46.690
It's called the Riemann
curvature tensor,

01:05:46.690 --> 01:05:48.490
and we will get to that fairly--

01:05:48.490 --> 01:05:50.810
actually, really, just
in a couple lectures.

01:05:50.810 --> 01:05:54.520
The other thing which
this is useful for

01:05:54.520 --> 01:06:01.180
is in all of my discussion
of the equivalence principle

01:06:01.180 --> 01:06:04.690
up to now, there's
been a weasel word

01:06:04.690 --> 01:06:06.940
that I have inserted
into much of the physics.

01:06:06.940 --> 01:06:10.250
I always said over
sufficiently small regions.

01:06:10.250 --> 01:06:10.750
OK?

01:06:10.750 --> 01:06:13.630
I say that trajectories begin
to deviate from one another

01:06:13.630 --> 01:06:16.290
when they get sufficiently
far away from one another.

01:06:16.290 --> 01:06:16.790
OK?

01:06:16.790 --> 01:06:18.385
And you should be
going, what the hell

01:06:18.385 --> 01:06:20.343
does sufficiently small,
sufficiently far away,

01:06:20.343 --> 01:06:22.070
what do all these things mean?

01:06:22.070 --> 01:06:22.600
OK?

01:06:22.600 --> 01:06:24.880
And the issue is you
need to have a scale.

01:06:24.880 --> 01:06:30.057
Well, this scale is going to
be set by the second derivative

01:06:30.057 --> 01:06:30.640
of the metric.

01:06:38.730 --> 01:06:47.080
So the size of the region
over which spacetime

01:06:47.080 --> 01:06:49.600
is inertial in this
coordinate system,

01:06:49.600 --> 01:07:03.890
in this representation
is approximately so

01:07:03.890 --> 01:07:08.060
imagine it's 1 over--
we can think of d2g

01:07:08.060 --> 01:07:11.375
as being 1 over
a length squared.

01:07:11.375 --> 01:07:12.800
So 1 over the
square root of that

01:07:12.800 --> 01:07:15.037
gives me a rough
idea of how long

01:07:15.037 --> 01:07:17.120
the curvature scale
associated with your spacetime

01:07:17.120 --> 01:07:17.730
actually is.

01:07:17.730 --> 01:07:20.900
And it tells you how big your
inertial region actually is.

01:07:25.160 --> 01:07:27.530
So we're going to make this
notion of curvature regress

01:07:27.530 --> 01:07:30.410
very, very soon.

01:07:30.410 --> 01:07:32.600
As a prelude to
this, we now need

01:07:32.600 --> 01:07:35.990
to start thinking about how
we do mathematics and physics

01:07:35.990 --> 01:07:37.100
on a curved manifold.

01:07:40.290 --> 01:07:46.125
So I'm going to start to
set up some of the issues

01:07:46.125 --> 01:07:47.000
that we need to face.

01:08:18.807 --> 01:08:20.640
So we're going to need
to define what I mean

01:08:20.640 --> 01:08:22.439
by a manifold that is curved.

01:08:22.439 --> 01:08:24.660
So a curved manifold
is going to simply

01:08:24.660 --> 01:08:30.479
be one in which initially
parallel trajectories do not

01:08:30.479 --> 01:08:32.069
remain parallel.

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:04.819
So an example is the surface
of a sphere, as I illustrated.

01:09:04.819 --> 01:09:07.189
You start somewhere on
the equator in Brazil.

01:09:07.189 --> 01:09:10.170
Your friend starts somewhere
on the equator in Africa.

01:09:10.170 --> 01:09:12.290
The two of you
start walking north.

01:09:12.290 --> 01:09:14.120
You are exactly
parallel when you take

01:09:14.120 --> 01:09:15.652
that first step of the equator.

01:09:15.652 --> 01:09:17.569
But your trajectories
cross at the North Pole.

01:09:25.600 --> 01:09:27.370
Interestingly, an
example that looks

01:09:27.370 --> 01:09:32.890
curved but is not, the
surface of a cylinder.

01:09:40.858 --> 01:09:41.359
OK?

01:09:41.359 --> 01:09:43.580
If I take two
lines, again, I need

01:09:43.580 --> 01:09:46.262
to imagine that this region
continues all the way up here.

01:09:46.262 --> 01:09:48.470
I make two lines that are
parallel to each other here

01:09:48.470 --> 01:09:50.840
and I have them extend
around this thing,

01:09:50.840 --> 01:09:53.899
they would remain parallel
the entire way out, OK?

01:09:53.899 --> 01:09:56.150
Another way of stating
that is that you can always

01:09:56.150 --> 01:10:00.500
take a cylinder and,
with an appropriate cut,

01:10:00.500 --> 01:10:03.710
but without tearing it, you
can flatten it out and make it

01:10:03.710 --> 01:10:07.372
into a simple sheet, a
perfectly flat sheet.

01:10:07.372 --> 01:10:09.830
You cannot do that with a sphere
without tearing it in some

01:10:09.830 --> 01:10:10.330
places.

01:10:14.040 --> 01:10:20.510
So what is going to begin
to complicate things

01:10:20.510 --> 01:10:24.890
is that we want to work with
vectors and tensors that

01:10:24.890 --> 01:10:26.825
live in this curved manifold.

01:10:39.170 --> 01:10:43.210
We haven't really thought too
carefully yet about the space.

01:10:43.210 --> 01:10:45.230
And let's just focus
on vectors for now.

01:10:45.230 --> 01:10:47.630
We haven't thought too carefully
about the space in which

01:10:47.630 --> 01:10:49.640
the vectors actually live.

01:10:49.640 --> 01:10:51.140
So implicit to
everything we have

01:10:51.140 --> 01:11:02.530
talked about up until now is
that we often regard vectors

01:11:02.530 --> 01:11:07.750
as objects that themselves
reside in a tangent space.

01:11:11.580 --> 01:11:13.500
OK, if I'm working in a
manifold that is flat,

01:11:13.500 --> 01:11:15.667
say it's the surface of
this board, OK, and just two

01:11:15.667 --> 01:11:19.050
dimensions, every
point on this board

01:11:19.050 --> 01:11:20.580
has the same tangent, all right?

01:11:20.580 --> 01:11:25.075
So if I draw a vector here and
I draw another vector over here,

01:11:25.075 --> 01:11:26.700
it's really easy for
me to compare them

01:11:26.700 --> 01:11:28.890
because they actually live
in the same space that

01:11:28.890 --> 01:11:31.410
is tangent to this board.

01:11:31.410 --> 01:11:34.410
If I'm on the
surface of a sphere,

01:11:34.410 --> 01:11:37.110
points that are tangent to
the sphere at the North Pole

01:11:37.110 --> 01:11:38.730
are very different
from points that

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:41.800
are tangent to the
sphere on the equator.

01:11:41.800 --> 01:11:44.783
So it becomes difficult for
me to actually compare fields

01:11:44.783 --> 01:11:46.950
when they are defined on a
curved surface like this.

01:12:23.670 --> 01:12:26.180
So this makes it a little
bit-- and so I'm just

01:12:26.180 --> 01:12:29.630
going to set up this problem,
and I will sketch the issue.

01:12:29.630 --> 01:12:32.855
And then we will resolve it
in our lecture on Tuesday.

01:12:32.855 --> 01:12:34.730
This makes it a little
bit complicated for me

01:12:34.730 --> 01:12:37.370
to take derivatives
of things like vectors

01:12:37.370 --> 01:12:40.700
when I'm working in
a curved manifold.

01:12:40.700 --> 01:12:42.740
So let's consider the
following situation.

01:12:47.250 --> 01:12:49.760
So I'm going to define some
curve, which I would just

01:12:49.760 --> 01:12:52.970
call gamma.

01:12:52.970 --> 01:12:55.320
It lives in a curved
space of some sort.

01:12:59.920 --> 01:13:01.990
I'm going to draw it
here on the board.

01:13:01.990 --> 01:13:06.200
But imagine that this is
on the surface of a sphere.

01:13:06.200 --> 01:13:07.490
OK?

01:13:07.490 --> 01:13:10.686
So here's the curve gamma.

01:13:10.686 --> 01:13:19.690
And let's say this point p
here has coordinates x alpha.

01:13:19.690 --> 01:13:24.060
And this point q
here has coordinates

01:13:24.060 --> 01:13:27.787
x alpha plus dx alpha.

01:13:27.787 --> 01:13:29.370
Suppose there's some
vector field that

01:13:29.370 --> 01:13:31.630
fills all this manifold.

01:13:31.630 --> 01:13:32.830
OK?

01:13:32.830 --> 01:13:37.910
And so let's say
the vector a looks

01:13:37.910 --> 01:13:41.858
like this here at the point p.

01:13:41.858 --> 01:13:48.140
And it looks like this
here at the point q.

01:13:48.140 --> 01:13:50.480
How do I take the derivative
of the vector field

01:13:50.480 --> 01:13:52.100
as I go from point p to point q?

01:14:11.350 --> 01:14:19.320
Well, your first guess
should basically just

01:14:19.320 --> 01:14:22.170
be do what you always
do when you first

01:14:22.170 --> 01:14:23.656
learn how to take a derivative.

01:15:10.280 --> 01:15:11.360
OK?

01:15:11.360 --> 01:15:14.380
So that would be a
notion of a derivative.

01:15:14.380 --> 01:15:16.740
There's nothing mathematically
wrong with that.

01:15:16.740 --> 01:15:17.240
OK?

01:15:17.240 --> 01:15:18.907
But we're going to
find that it gives us

01:15:18.907 --> 01:15:22.690
problems for the same reason
that we ran into problems when

01:15:22.690 --> 01:15:24.900
we began working
with vector spaces

01:15:24.900 --> 01:15:26.270
and curvilinear coordinates.

01:15:26.270 --> 01:15:27.520
OK?

01:15:27.520 --> 01:15:31.660
If I want this to be a
tensorial object in the same way

01:15:31.660 --> 01:15:33.918
that we have been defining
tensors all along here,

01:15:33.918 --> 01:15:35.210
I'm going to run into problems.

01:15:35.210 --> 01:15:36.880
So let me just actually
demonstrate what

01:15:36.880 --> 01:15:40.268
happens if I try to do this.

01:15:40.268 --> 01:15:42.310
So the key bit, the way
we want to think about it

01:15:42.310 --> 01:15:45.790
is that the points p and q
don't have the same tangent

01:15:45.790 --> 01:15:56.640
space, which is a
fancy way of saying

01:15:56.640 --> 01:15:59.310
that, as I move from
point p to point q,

01:15:59.310 --> 01:16:01.260
the basis vectors are moving.

01:16:01.260 --> 01:16:03.379
They're starting to point
in different directions.

01:16:17.870 --> 01:16:19.733
So if this were to be--

01:16:19.733 --> 01:16:21.400
like I said,
mathematically, if you just

01:16:21.400 --> 01:16:23.050
want to get that
derivative, that

01:16:23.050 --> 01:16:26.810
is a quantity which has a
mathematical meaning, OK?

01:16:26.810 --> 01:16:29.140
But it's not the component
of a tensor, which

01:16:29.140 --> 01:16:31.990
we have called out as having a
particularly important meaning

01:16:31.990 --> 01:16:34.840
in this geometric construction
of physics that we are doing.

01:16:34.840 --> 01:16:37.905
And so if this were
to be tensorial,

01:16:37.905 --> 01:16:40.280
then I should be able to switch
to new coordinates, which

01:16:40.280 --> 01:16:57.000
I'll designate with primes, such
that the following was true.

01:17:04.390 --> 01:17:08.050
The reason why this
doesn't actually work

01:17:08.050 --> 01:17:10.000
is I'm going to
demand that alpha--

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:13.330
excuse me-- that a is, in fact,
actually already tensorial.

01:17:13.330 --> 01:17:13.830
OK?

01:17:13.830 --> 01:17:15.330
It's the compound
of a vector, which

01:17:15.330 --> 01:17:16.830
is a particular kind of tensor.

01:17:23.400 --> 01:17:30.540
So I'm going to demand
that the following be true.

01:17:33.470 --> 01:17:40.760
And I'm going to demand
that my derivatives,

01:17:40.760 --> 01:17:41.970
they are just derivatives.

01:17:41.970 --> 01:17:44.340
They do the usual rule
Jacobian rule when

01:17:44.340 --> 01:17:47.310
I switch coordinate systems.

01:17:47.310 --> 01:17:49.302
And so skipping a
line of algebra,

01:17:49.302 --> 01:17:50.760
which you can get
in my notes, this

01:17:50.760 --> 01:17:53.220
is actually very similar to
the notes I've already posted.

01:17:53.220 --> 01:17:54.720
When you work this
out, you're going

01:17:54.720 --> 01:18:15.280
to find you get one
term that's correct,

01:18:15.280 --> 01:18:18.790
but you get another
term that involves

01:18:18.790 --> 01:18:21.190
a derivative of your coordinate
transformation matrix.

01:18:26.220 --> 01:18:29.432
And this is an actual term,
spoils the tensorialness

01:18:29.432 --> 01:18:30.140
of this quantity.

01:18:34.100 --> 01:18:40.510
The way we are going
to cure this is we

01:18:40.510 --> 01:18:46.350
are going to demand that if
we want our derivatives to be

01:18:46.350 --> 01:18:51.420
derivatives that comport with a
notion of taking tensor objects

01:18:51.420 --> 01:18:55.110
and getting other tensor objects
out of them, before we take

01:18:55.110 --> 01:18:58.530
the derivative, we have to
have some way of transporting

01:18:58.530 --> 01:19:01.020
the objects to the same
location in the manifold,

01:19:01.020 --> 01:19:02.850
where I can then compare them.

01:19:34.190 --> 01:19:39.400
So here's one example
of a notion of transport

01:19:39.400 --> 01:19:40.180
that we could use.

01:19:45.920 --> 01:19:48.920
So here's a at point q.

01:19:48.920 --> 01:19:51.490
There's a at point p.

01:19:51.490 --> 01:19:55.637
Notion one that we'll talk about
is known as parallel transport.

01:20:03.750 --> 01:20:06.550
What that's essentially going
to mean is I'm going to say,

01:20:06.550 --> 01:20:09.465
well, let's take one of
these guys, either q or p.

01:20:09.465 --> 01:20:11.490
The way it's drawn in
my notes, I've used q.

01:20:11.490 --> 01:20:12.810
But it could be either.

01:20:12.810 --> 01:20:15.090
And let's imagine
I slide it parallel

01:20:15.090 --> 01:20:42.120
to itself until this gives me a
alpha from q transported to p.

01:20:42.120 --> 01:20:45.140
And then I define a derivative
with that transported notion

01:20:45.140 --> 01:20:46.370
of the vector.

01:20:46.370 --> 01:20:49.970
Now notice I've called
this notion one.

01:20:49.970 --> 01:20:51.890
You can take from
that this idea of how

01:20:51.890 --> 01:20:54.210
I transport the vector
from one place to the other

01:20:54.210 --> 01:20:55.430
to do this comparison.

01:20:55.430 --> 01:20:57.800
I cannot uniquely define it.

01:20:57.800 --> 01:21:00.087
There are, in fact, multiple
ways you can do this.

01:21:00.087 --> 01:21:01.670
We're going to talk
about two that are

01:21:01.670 --> 01:21:04.720
useful at the level of 8.962.

01:21:04.720 --> 01:21:06.470
In principle, I imagine
you could probably

01:21:06.470 --> 01:21:08.760
come up with a whole butt
load of these things.

01:21:08.760 --> 01:21:11.150
These are two that
the physics picks out

01:21:11.150 --> 01:21:12.740
as being particularly
useful for us

01:21:12.740 --> 01:21:14.930
for the analysis that
we are going to do.

01:21:14.930 --> 01:21:15.530
OK?

01:21:15.530 --> 01:21:16.910
So we'll pick it up
there on Tuesday.

01:21:16.910 --> 01:21:18.368
We're going to
start by coming back

01:21:18.368 --> 01:21:20.510
to this notion of I want
to differentiate a vector

01:21:20.510 --> 01:21:22.540
field in a curved manifold.

01:21:22.540 --> 01:21:24.950
And let me just state
before we conclude,

01:21:24.950 --> 01:21:29.030
now that I've transported
a from q to p,

01:21:29.030 --> 01:21:31.220
they share the
same tangent space.

01:21:31.220 --> 01:21:33.650
Since they share the
same tangent space,

01:21:33.650 --> 01:21:35.030
I can compare them more easily.

01:21:35.030 --> 01:21:37.520
That allows me to make a
sensible derivative that

01:21:37.520 --> 01:21:40.280
respects all the notions
of what a tensor should be.

01:21:40.280 --> 01:21:42.940
We'll pick it up from
there on Tuesday.